      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Encroachment issues with neighboring lots are a headache, and the city handles them with a strict adherence to the established property lines and setback requirements. If your grocery's footprint or even its delivery staging area starts creeping into the setback area or onto a neighbor's land, it's considered a violation, not just a minor annoyance. The city inspectors are usually quick to notice these boundary infractions, and they'll issue notices of violation, requiring you to rectify the encroachment immediately.\n\nThese disputes are often resolved by requiring the property owner to either move the structure back to the legal footprint or, in rare cases, negotiate a formal easement with the neighbor—though that's usually a messy process, not the clean, quick solution a small shop needs. It's much safer to keep your delivery zone entirely within the permitted commercial footprint, well back from the property line.\n\nIt's a good idea to have a surveyor mark those lines *before* you start any heavy construction, because once the concrete is poured, pulling it back is a monumental task. Don't let the delivery trucks become a source of neighborhood conflict, or you'll have a bigger headache than a whole siege of territorial, property-line-defying little",
